The traditional StockX marketplace essentially already relies upon this legal doctrine. The question now before us is how this existing legal framework will apply to the use of NFTs to facilitate the sale of branded physical assets.

Arguably, StockX may use the Nike trademarks as is necessary to accurately identify the origin of Nike shoes and to provide a marketplace for the resale of authentic Nike shoes, so long as the use of the mark does not suggest an affiliation or endorsement from Nike.
‚Äú‚Ä¶[I]t is undisputed that trademark owners cannot use trademark law to prevent the resale of authentic, trademarked goods.‚Äù Tiffany Inc. v. eBay, Inc., 576 F. Supp 2d 463 (S.D.N.Y 2008).
In another example, in Tiffany Inc. v. eBay, Inc., the Court held that eBay‚Äôs use of the Tiffany mark on their homepage for purposes of advertising was nominative fair use.

Nominative fair use allows the use of another‚Äôs trademark in advertising the availability of trademarked goods. This is from the New Kids on the Block v. News Am. Publ‚Äôg, Inc., 971 F.2d 302 (9th Cir. 1992) case.

the 1) product or service is not readily identifiable without use of the trademark; 2) use only so much of the mark as is reasonably necessary to identify the product or service; and 3) use of the mark does not suggest sponsorship or endorsement by the trademark owner.
Nominative fair use permits use of another‚Äôs trademark to refer to the trademark owner‚Äôs goods and services associated with the mark. Nominative fair use generally is permissible as long as ...
Instead, the complaint alleges only trademark claims and related state law unfair competition claims. Under trademark law, StockX may be able to rely on the concept of ‚Äúnominative fair use.‚Äù

Generally, a seller‚Äôs exclusive rights to the sale of physical goods extends only to the so-called ‚Äúfirst sale.‚Äù However, the ‚Äòfirst sale‚Äô doctrine arises under copyright law. Interestingly Nike did not assert any claims premised under copyright law.

I think the Nike v. StockX case raises novel legal issues, including how the sale of an NFT representing a physical asset can be used to trade an underlying physical good, as well as how this fact-set should be viewed from a legal perspective.
Nike just filed an interesting complaint against StockX in the SDNY regarding StockX's new Vault NFT platform which uses NFTs to trade authentic physical shoes (including Nike shoes).

@Jon_Sharples Hard to speak to comparative odds of success... I will say that typically proof of "fame" for purposes of dilution can be difficult. Herm√®s alleges this is essentially admitted in a Defendant interview ‚ÄúThe Birkin Bag by Herm√®s is such a status symbol across the globe.‚Äù Para 100
The full Complaint is located here and the case is before Judge Alison Nathan in the SDNY: https://t.co/FTG12OzQkA

The dilution claim is interesting because it may allow an avenue for the court to find liability even in the absence of consumer confusion, if METABIRKIN "dilutes the distinctive quality of the BIRKIN Mark" and related goodwill stemming from the alleged fame of the BIRKIN mark.

The complaint alleges 7 counts, including trademark infringement, false designation of origin, dilution (claiming fame for the BIRKIN mark), cybersquatting under the ACPA, and NY common law trademark infringement and dilution.

Herm√®s acknowledges that "a digital image connected to an NFT may reflect some artistic creativity," but counters that "the title of 'artist' does not confer a license" to use the BIRKIN trademark to mislead consumers and identify Herm√®s as the true source of BIRKINs.

Herm√®s also expresses concern over a ‚Äúdecentralized METABIRKINS exchange‚Äù which could potentially sell METABIRKINS NFTs without the need for NFT marketplaces like OpenSea (which has already removed the NFTs from their marketplace), Rarible, LooksRare, or Zora (i.e. CryptoPhunks)

Herm√®s alleges that the advertisement and sale of NFTs under the METABIRKINS brand will "ultimately preempt Herm√®s‚Äô ability to offer products and services in virtual marketplaces that are uniquely associated with Herm√®s and meet Herm√®s‚Äô quality standards."

Herm√®s argues that while they have not yet
minted and sold Herm√®s NFTs, "consumers would expect that NFTs featuring famous brands are affiliated with those brands, or wonder why the famous brands are permitting such dilutive use of their valuable assets" and think less of them.

Well perhaps it was inevitable that Herm√®s would sue the MetaBirkin NFT project, but here we go...
